revision.text:
{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}} {{Use British English|date=May 2015}} '''Arthur Ronald Butler''' (1916 – 7 November 2003)<ref name=LP>"A. Ronald (Ron) Butler RDP Hon FRPSL 1916–2003." in ''[[The London Philatelist]]'', Vol. 113, No. 1312, January–February 2004, p. 2.</ref> was a British [[philatelist]] who was President of the [[Royal Philatelic Society London]] from 1978 to 1980. He was a specialist in the stamps of [[Postage stamps and postal history of Australia|Australia]] and in 1978 was awarded the [[Crawford Medal]] for his work ''The departmental stamps of South Australia''.<ref>''The Society's medals and honorary fellowship''. The Royal Philatelic Society London, 2009, p. 4.</ref>
In 1975, at Leicester, Butler signed the [[Roll of Distinguished Philatelists]].
==Outside philately== Butler was an engineer by profession, first working for the toy manufacturers Lotts Bricks. During World War II he served in the Royal Air Force, and afterwards joined the [[Royal Aircraft Establishment|Royal Aeronautical Establishment]] at Farnborough. At this time he was involved in investigating crashes of the [[De Havilland Comet|Comet]] aircraft.<ref name=LP/>
In 1968 Butler worked for the [[Decimal Day|Decimal Currency Board]] where he was involved in designing the shape of the British 50p piece.<ref name=LP/>
==Selected publications== *''The departmental stamps of South Australia.'' London: Royal Philatelic Society, 1978. *''The Roll of Distinguished Philatelists''. The British Philatelic Federation Limited, 1990. (Addenda 1994 and 1999)
