{{Infobox officeholder | name = Darryl W. Perry | image = File:Darryl W. Perry.png | office = Chair of the [[Libertarian Party of New Hampshire]] | term_start = September 2016 | party = [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] | otherparty = [[Boston Tea Party (political party)|Boston Tea]] | birth_place = [[Birmingham, Alabama]], U.S. | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|02|07}} | alma_mater = [[Jefferson State Community College]] |website = [http://darrylwperry.com/ DarrylWPerry.com] }} '''Darryl W. Perry''' (born February 7, 1978) is an American activist, author, radio host and politician.
== Early life == Daryl W. Perry was born and raised in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], and the surrounding area, graduating from [[Hewitt-Trussville High School]] in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://darrylwperry.com/bio/|title=Bio|date=17 April 2017|website=darrylwperry.com|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref>
Darryl attended [[Jefferson State Community College]] on a scholarship with the Speech Team (Forensics Team), and later on a Management Scholarship with WJSR-FM, the college radio station. Darryl was station manager from the summer of 1997 until he graduated in 1998.
==Career== He hosts the daily newscast FPPradioNews, the podcast Peace, Love, Liberty Radio, the weekly news podcast FPP Freedom Minute, and is a regular co-host on Free Talk Live.
Perry is a co-founder of the New Hampshire Liberty Party, and was on the National Committee of the [[Boston Tea Party]] from 2008-2012, twice serving as chair. Perry later sought the [[Libertarian Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Libertarian Party presidential nomination]] on a platform as the only "real" Libertarian running. To fund his candidacy, Perry accepted donations only in valuables not sanctioned by a government, such as encrypted electronic currencies or non-coin metals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cointelegraph.com/news/gary-johnson-wins-libertarian-nomination-only-major-candidate-to-accept-bitcoin-donations |title=Gary Johnson Wins Libertarian Nomination, Only Major Candidate to Accept Bitcoin Donations |last=Valenzuela |first=Joël |date=May 30, 2016 |website=The Cointelegraph |publisher= |access-date=January 5, 2017 |quote=Darryl W. Perry, former Libertarian presidential campaign, famously accepted donations exclusively in cryptocurrency, precious metals, and other non-governmental stores of value.}}</ref>
After the [[2016 Libertarian National Convention|Libertarian Convention]] and the nomination of [[Gary Johnson]], he voiced concerns over Johnson's vice presidential nominee [[Bill Weld]], citing the failure of the [[Reform Party of the United States|Reform Party]] as evidence that The Libertarian Party needed a more consistent message and suggesting Will Coley or [[Larry Sharpe (politician)|Larry Sharpe]] as more suitable running mates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4601274/darryl-w-perrys-concession-speech|title=Darryl W. Perry's concession speech|website=C-SPAN.org|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> He confronted Weld before the nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bbMw1ds8JAA|title=Darryl Perry confronts William Weld|first=|last=Jeff Wood|date=1 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=6 January 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref> After the convention he announced a limited write-in campaign in 17 states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://independentpoliticalreport.com/2016/09/darryl-w-perry-announces-limited-presidential-write-in-campaign/|title=Darryl W. Perry Announces Limited Presidential Write-In Campaign|date=29 September 2016|website=independentpoliticalreport.com|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> He received either 5<ref>[https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=780309&ShowAllCand=Y https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=780309&ShowAllCand=Y]</ref> or 3 votes overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thegreenpapers.com/G16/PresidentVoteByParty.phtml|title=The Green Papers 2016 General Election Presidential Popular Vote and FEC Total Receipts by Party|website=www.thegreenpapers.com}}</ref>
==Political positions== Perry is considered a "hard-core" libertarian, who expressed dismay that [[Gary Johnson]] won the Libertarian's 2016 Presidential nomination.<ref name=cbc>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/libertarian-party-gary-johnson-donald-trump-hillary-clinton-spoiler-1.3612883 |title=Libertarian Gary Johnson could swing votes from Donald Trump, Hillary Clinton |last=Kwong |first=Matt |date=June 5, 2016 |website=CBCNEWS |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |access-date=January 5, 2017}}</ref> He supports the decriminalization of recreational drugs, stating they "should be as legal as tomatoes."<ref name=cbc /> He supports a [[non-interventionist]] foreign policy.<ref>http://fpp.cc/non-intervention-its-good-enough-for-you-why-not-the-nation/</ref> Perry has an [[Anarcho-capitalism|anarcho-capitalist]] platform, calling the United States Government "the world's biggest terrorist organization" and advocates abolishing the United States Government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W1ugtes7ZYA|title=Libertarian presidential candidates face off in RT-hosted debate|first=|last=RT America|date=12 May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=6 January 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>
