'''Kona Williams''' (born ca 1978) is a [[forensic pathologist]], the first [[First Nations]] person in that profession in Canada.<ref name=star>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/2016/09/25/meet-canadas-first-aboriginal-forensic-pathologist.html |title=Meet Canada’s first aboriginal forensic pathologist |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=September 25, 2016}}</ref>
The daughter of Gordon Williams, a [[Cree]] from [[Peguis First Nation]] in [[Manitoba]], and Karen Jacobs-Williams, a [[Mohawk people|Mohawk]] from [[Kahnawake]], she was born in [[Ottawa]]. She studied medicine at the [[University of Ottawa]], received her [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] in 2009, and spent five more years as an anatomical pathology resident there. She continued with a post-graduate fellowship in the department of laboratory medicine and pathobiology at the [[University of Toronto]]. In 2016, she was hired by the Ontario Forensic Pathology Service, which provides pathology services for the Ontario police forces.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uottawa.ca/tabaret/en/content/forensic-pathology-pioneer |title=A forensic pathology pioneer |work=Tabaret |publisher=University of Ottawa}}</ref><ref name=star/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.utoronto.ca/news/canadas-first-indigenous-forensic-pathologist-u-ts-kona-williams |title=Canada's first Indigenous forensic pathologist: U of T's Kona Williams |work=U of T News |date=February 18, 2016}}</ref>
