{{Infobox person |name = Mary Young Cheney Greeley |birth_date = 1811 or 1814 |birth_name = Mary Young Cheney |birth_place = [[Litchfield, Connecticut]] |children = 7 (5 died in childhood) |death_date = 29 October 1872 |death_place = [[New York City]], U.S. |known_for = Wife of [[Horace Greeley]]; [[suffragette]] |movement = Suffrage |parents = |resting_place = [[Green-Wood]] |spouse(s) = Horace Greeley (1836&ndash;1872) }} '''Mary Young Cheney Greeley''' (1811 or 1814 – 1872) was the wife of American newspaper editor [[Horace Greeley]].
Little is known of her early life. She was briefly a schoolteacher, and later an intermittent suffragette and [[Spiritualism|spiritualist]]. She is reported to have been mentally unstable for much of her life. The date of her birth is uncertain, with some sources stating 1811 and others 1814.<ref name="Mrs obituary"/><ref>[https://www.litchfieldhistoricalsociety.org/ledger/students/3836 ''Litchfield Ledger'']</ref><ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=DEVJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA280&lpg=PA280&dq=Mary+Young+Cheney+Greeley+1811&source=bl&ots=4FzbCFqsKZ&sig=3XokKQwe0_v7hau90yHyY-N711k&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjh6ejImOzeAhUHGTQIHcCjBfs4ChDoATACegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=Mary%20Young%20Cheney%20Greeley%201811&f=false ''Correspondence of Henry D. Thoreau'']</ref><ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=JmRgDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA175&lpg=PA175&dq=Mary+Young+Cheney+Greeley+1814&source=bl&ots=Em980F_2gp&sig=RUqyj-GYlQ4jZornWyPD5Iohkgs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiWjJnYmOzeAhUzPn0KHbc0BKAQ6AEwD3oECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Mary%20Young%20Cheney%20Greeley%201814&f=false ''Mark Twain's Letters'']</ref>
They married in [[Warrenton, North Carolina]], on July 5, 1836. Early in their marriage he used her $5000 in savings to fund his first private newspaper.{{Citation needed|date=October 2013}}
The marriage was not a happy one, and her oppressive relationship with her husband colored her life. He had little say in the running of the house, and avoided his wife and their house. However, he kept her almost constantly pregnant, but took no responsibility for the children. Five of their seven children died quite young, at least some of them of neglect.<ref name="woodhull">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FAPg5QVvisoC&pg=PA56 |title=Other Powers: The Age of Suffrage, Spiritualism, and the Scandalous Victoria Woodhull|publisher=Books.google.com |date=1998-04-21 |accessdate=2010-11-18|isbn=9780060953324}}</ref>
<includeonly>Mary </includeonly>Greeley was an advocate of the [[Graham Diet]] and a [[Spiritualism (religious movement)|Spiritualist]]. Her behavior suggests she may have had [[clinical depression]] and [[Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder]].<ref name="woodhull"/> She believed her son Arthur Young Greeley, known as "Pickie",<ref>Hon. S.S. Randall, "[http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1872/12/25/page/7/article/personal-recollections-of-mr-greeley Personal Recollections of Mr. Greeley]." New York ''Telegraph'', reprinted in the Chicago ''Tribune'', December 25, 1872, p. 7.</ref> was a [[Mediumship|spirit medium]]. She kept him isolated from the world and from other children, and constantly demanded that he relay communications from the afterlife. As he grew older he began to express a fierce anger towards his mother.<ref name="woodhull"/><ref>Marvin Olasky, ''[https://www.worldmag.com/world/olasky/centralideas/chap7.html Central Ideas in the Development of American Journalism: A Narrative History]'' (Routledge, 2015), chapter 7. Entire text online at worldmag.com.</ref> After his death at age five from cholera, she hired the 11-year-old [[Fox sisters|Kate Fox]] to stay at her house and contact him. Ms. Fox later wrote that she too disliked Mrs. Greeley intensely.<ref name="woodhull"/>
She suffered from "[[Tuberculosis|consumptive lung disease]]" for the last 20 years of her life, and died from it on October 30, 1872. Her husband, who was running for [[President of the United States]] at the time, died 30 days later.<ref name="Mrs obituary">{{cite news|title=OBITUARY.; Mrs. Horace Greeley|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1872/10/31/archives/obituary-mrs-horace-greeley.html|accessdate=21 October 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 31, 1872|location=New York, NY, US}}</ref>
