{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}} {{Infobox ice hockey player | name = Riley Tufte | image = | image_caption = | image_size = 225px | team = [[Minnesota-Duluth Bulldogs men's ice hockey|Minnesota Duluth]] | league = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] | position = [[Winger (ice hockey)|Left Wing]] | former_teams = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1998|4|10}} | birth_place = [[Coon Rapids, Minnesota]], U.S. | height_ft = 6 | height_in = 6 | weight_lb = 215 | draft = 25th overall | draft_year = 2016 | draft_team = [[Dallas Stars]] | career_start = TBD | career_end = }} '''Riley Jack Tufte''' (born April 10, 1998) is an American [[ice hockey]] player for the [[Minnesota–Duluth Bulldogs men's ice hockey|University of Minnesota Duluth]]. He formerly played for the [[Fargo Force]] (2014–16). Tufte was drafted in the first round, 25th overall, of the [[2016 NHL Entry Draft]] by the [[Dallas Stars]].
==Personal life== Tufte was born and grew up in [[Coon Rapids, Minnesota]] with three siblings and his mother Amy, who is a nurse.<ref name = diabetes> {{cite news|last1=Russo|first1=Michael|title=NHL draft prospect Riley Tufte is the pride of Blaine|url=http://www.startribune.com/nhl-draft-prospect-riley-tufte-is-the-pride-of-blaine/383887521/|accessdate=January 6, 2018|publisher=Star Tribune|date=June 22, 2016}}</ref> At the age of 11, Tufte was diagnosed with [[Diabetes mellitus type 1|Type 1 diabetes]].<ref name = diabetes/><ref>{{cite news|title=Diabetes doesn't slow down Blaine's Riley Tufte|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/2016/01/13/diabetes-doesnt-slow-down-blaines-riley-tufte/78771800/|accessdate=January 6, 2018|publisher=USA Today|date=January 13, 2016|location=Blaine, Minn}}</ref> As a child, he received an inspirational letter from retired NHL player [[Toby Petersen]] who also suffered from diabetes.<ref name = diabetes/>
==Playing career==
Tufte played for Blaine High School in Minnesota, where he was awarded the 2015–16 Mr. Hockey Award in his senior year after he led all of Minnesota Class AA in goals scored.<ref name = "fargo"/> He also played two seasons for the [[Fargo Force]] of the [[USHL]], accumulating 19 points in 34 games, before deciding to go back to high school for his senior year.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Engels|first1=Eric|title=Prospect of Interest: The 411 on Riley Tufte|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/prospect-interest-411-riley-tufte/|website=sportsnet.ca|accessdate=January 6, 2018|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref> In March 2016, Tufte was invited to Team USA's 2016 National Junior Evaluation Camp, to prepare for the [[2016 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]], however he broke his wrist during camp and could not play.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wellens|first1=Matt|title=College men's hockey: Tufte breaks wrist at national junior team camp, doesn't expect to miss time with UMD|url=http://www.duluthnewstribune.com/sports/hockey/4086383-college-mens-hockey-tufte-breaks-wrist-national-junior-team-camp-doesnt-expect|website=duluthnewstribune.com|accessdate=January 8, 2018|date=April 2, 2016}}</ref> Despite this, Tufte became the highest NHL draft pick in the history of the [[Fargo Force]] when he was drafted in the first round of the [[2016 NHL Entry Draft]].<ref name = "fargo">{{cite web|title=TUFTE SELECTED 25TH OVERALL IN NHL DRAFT|url=http://www.fargoforce.com/news_article/show/665027-tufte-selected-25th-overall-in-nhl-draft|website=fargoforce.com|accessdate=January 6, 2018|date=June 28, 2016}}</ref> Instead of going pro right away, Tufte decided to pursue higher education at the [[University of Minnesota Duluth]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hunt|first1=Steve|title=Stars' Riley Tufte puts NHL dream on hold|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/stars-prospect-riley-tufte-puts-nhl-dream-on-hold/c-281147656|website=nhl.com|publisher=Dallas Stars|accessdate=January 6, 2018|location=Frisco, Texas|date=July 10, 2016}}</ref>
Tufte missed the beginning of his freshman season due to an injury but he completed the season with 16 points.<ref name = "prospect report">{{cite web|last1=Stepneski|first1=Mark|title=Prospect Report: Riley Tufte off to strong start in NCAA|url=https://www.nhl.com/stars/news/prospect-report-riley-tufte-off-to-strong-start-in-ncaa/c-292192038|website=NHL.com|accessdate=March 26, 2018|date=October 23, 2017}}</ref> He was off to a stronger start in his sophomore season,<ref name = "prospect report"/> leading the team in scoring as they advance through the [[NCAA Men's Ice Hockey Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stepneski|first1=Mark|title=Prospect Report: Cecconi, Tufte advance to Frozen Four|url=https://www.nhl.com/stars/news/dallas-stars-prospect-report-march-26/c-297330878|website=nhl.com|accessdate=March 26, 2018|date=March 26, 2018}}</ref>
==International play==
Tufte's played in both the 2014 Under-17 Five Nations Cup and the [[2014 World U-17 Hockey Challenge (November)|2014 World U-17 Hockey Challenge]].<ref name = "Team USA bio">{{cite web|title=Riley Tufte|url=https://teamusa.usahockey.com/page/show/3813223-2018-wjc-riley-tufte|website=teamusa.usahockey.com|accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> He helped Team USA place second in the 2014 Under-17 Five Nations Cup.<ref>{{cite web|title=USA Takes Second Place in U-17 Five Nations, Beating Germany, 8-2|url=https://teamusa.usahockey.com/news_article/show/410769?referrer_id=2675746|website=teamusa.usahockey.com|accessdate=March 26, 2018|date=August 17, 2014}}</ref>
Tufte competed in the [[2015 Ivan Hlinka Memorial Tournament]] for Team USA, who finished fifth in the tournament.<ref name = "Team USA bio"/> He later competed at the [[2018 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]] where he helped Team USA secure a bronze medal.<ref name = "Team USA bio"/>
